9 AS INTRODUCED
10 An Act relating to schools; requiring the State
Department of Education to develop a common course
11 number system for public and charter schools;
establishing number system requirements; allowing the
12 Department to use the Classification of Secondary
School Courses as a resource for the number system;
13 stating which courses to include in the number
system; prescribing design requirements; providing
14 six-digit code composition recommendations; allowing
schools to seek approval for nonstandard courses;
15 requiring waivers for nonstandard courses; mandating
the creation of a panel to review waivers; naming
16 appointors for panel; requiring panel appointments to
be made by certain date; establishing panel member
17 limits; providing for codification; and providing an
effective date.
18
19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 11-103.17 of Title 70, unless
22 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. In consultation with the Oklahoma Department of Career and
24 Technology Education and the State Regents of Higher Education, the
HB3031 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 Stat e Department of Education shall develop, implement, and maintain
2 a common course number system to be used by all public schools and
3 charter schools of this state for all courses taught at the
4 secondary level that are eligible for credit towards a high school
5 diploma, and are aligned with the Oklahoma Academic Standards.
6 Courses granted a nonstandard course waiver under subsection F of
7 this section shall also be assigned a common course number by the
8 State Department of Education.
9 B. The common course number system shall be designed to
10 describe course offerings and to provide a coherent means for
11 classifying courses across the state between school districts. At
12 the discretion of the State Department of Education, the
13 Classification of Secondary School Courses (CSSC) may be utilized as
14 a resource to create a general inventory of courses taught at the
15 secondary level. Vocational, academic, elective, apprenticeship,
16 and general courses offered for credit shall be included in the
17 common course number list and coding.
18 C. The State Department of Education shall design the common
19 course number system to provide school administrators, state and
20 local education stakeholders, and policy officials a resource to
21 convert course offerings, make comparisons of course offerings,
22 input information from transcripts, streamline master teaching
23 schedules, and to provide families usable communication tools for
24 graduation pathways in practical and efficient formats.
HB3031 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 D. The following six-digit numerical code composition is
2 recommended to the State Department of Education to identify each
3 course:
4 1. The first two digits identify the main program area subject
5 such as mathematics, English language arts, history, and others;
6 2. The second set of two digits represent the set of Oklahoma
7 Academic Standards within the main program area subject that align
8 with the course such as Algebra 1, Literature, Economics, and
9 others; and
10 3. The final two numbers may be used by school districts to
11 differentiate between class sections for the same course.
12 E. The common course number system required by this section
13 shall be developed no later than March 31, 2027, and shall be
14 implemented in public schools and public charter schools beginning
15 with the 2027-2028 school year.
16 F. A school may offer a course for credit that does not fully
17 align with the Oklahoma Academic Standards if the school submits a
18 Nonstandard Course Waiver to the waiver panel described in
19 subsection G of this section, and the waiver is approved.
20 G. 1. There shall be created a panel for the purposes of
21 reviewing and approving or disapproving Nonstandard Course Waivers
22 submitted by schools. The panel shall consist of seven (7) members
23 with knowledge of, experience with, or expertise in the Oklahoma
24
HB3031 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 Acad emic Standards or curriculum adoption. The panel members shall
2 be designees selected and appointed by the following:
3 a. the Chancellor of the Regents of Higher Education,
4 b. the Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives,
5 c. the President Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma State
6 Senate,
7 d. the Superintendent of Public Instruction,
8 e. the Director of Career and Technology Education,
9 f. the Secretary of Education, and
10 g. the Oklahoma State School Boards Association (OSSBA).
11 The OSSBA's panel designee shall be a locally elected
12 school board member.
13 2. Initial appointments to the panel shall be made by March 31,
14 2027. Each designee appointed under this subsection shall serve at
15 the pleasure of the appointing authority, but shall not serve more
16 than six (6) consecutive years.
17 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
